{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_01FRRWBRnDX75kgj1SPfBBWZ","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"OK so I can see the full picture now. The unstaged changes to handler.go include the `extractFilePath` function and the fix to use it when reading step content. The staged changes are unrelated route cleanup.\n\nNow let me look at the original code (before the unstaged changes) by checking the staged version:\n\nIn the original code (before unstaged changes), `handleAPIStepContent`:\n```go\nif prompt := step.Config[\"prompt\"]; prompt != \"\" {\n    data, err := os.ReadFile(filepath.Join(dir, prompt))\n```\n\nSo the original code used `prompt` directly (which is `file(\".cloche/prompts/implement.md\")`) as a file path without extracting the actual path first. That would fail because `file(\".cloche/prompts/implement.md\")` is not a valid file path.\n\n\nThe same issue appears with `step.Config[\"command\"]` and `step.Config[\"script\"]` — neither of them use `extractFilePath` either. The unstaged changes already have the fix in place, but if the bug still exists in the current working tree, I need to double-check what's actually in the file. Let me look at the current `handleAPIStepContent` implementation more carefully to see what's really happening. I'm looking at the fetch request that retrieves the step content and displays it in the drawer, sanitizing the HTML by escaping ampersands and angle brackets before rendering it in a pre tag.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1121,"cache_read_input_tokens":48664,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":1121},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"fe399e8d-ac34-4834-9459-9cc0582e00b8","uuid":"9acd3e34-a49d-4773-a682-69916bfcaa3a"}
